Thanks for sharing this example! The generic type parameters were stripped by HTML encoding in the issue body, but the intent is clear.

In .NET 8 with current F# interop, you can call `SampleInto` from C# **without** `FuncConvert` by passing a plain lambda — the extension method accepts `Func(Series(DateTime, V), V)` directly:

```csharp
using Deedle;
using Microsoft.FSharp.Core;

var data = new SeriesBuilder(DateTime, double)();
var date = DateTime.UtcNow;
for (int i = 0; i < 90; i++)
{
    data.Add(date, Random.Shared.NextDouble() * 5 + 5);
    date = date.AddSeconds(1);
}

// Direct lambda — no FuncConvert needed in modern .NET
var samples = data.Series.SampleInto(
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30),
    Direction.Forward,
    s => Stats.Mean(s));
```

The overload `SampleInto(V)(Series(DateTime, V), TimeSpan, Direction, Func<_, _>)` is already designed for C# callers, so a plain `Func(Series(DateTime, double), double)` lambda works.

If you still see a type error with the direct lambda (e.g. the compiler can't infer the generic parameter), you can annotate it explicitly:
```csharp
Func(Series(DateTime, double), double) agg = s => Stats.Mean(s);
var samples = data.Series.SampleInto(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30), Direction.Forward, agg);
```

The `FuncConvert.FromFunc` approach you found also works and is a valid fallback for cases where inference fails.

